\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each 8x8 block, the following steps are applied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Direction Search
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The direction search evaluates equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:direction-variance3"

\end_inset

 for each of the 8 directions, with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N_{d,k}}$
\end_inset

 factor being replaced by a 10-bit multiply.
 In total, the search for all 8 directions requires the following arithmetic
 operations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The pixel accumulations in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:direction-variance3"

\end_inset

 are 418 adds of 8-bit signed values, with results that fit in 11 bits.
 There's a maximum of 8 values contributing to each sums.
 (there are simplifications that can save 128 adds using intermediate sums).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The result of 1) is 90 11-bit partial sums.
 Each is squared (so 90 11-bit multiplies), with the result being 21-bit
 unsigned values.
 Each of these is multiplied by one of eight different 10-bit constants,
 with the result guaranteed to fit in 27 bits.
 Since some lines use the same constant and are eventually added together,
 only 34 multiplies by constants are needed after simplification.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There are another 86 adds from the results of step 2), resulting in 8 29-bit
 unsigned values.
 There's a maximum of 15 values contributing to each of these sums.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The resulting values in 3) are compared to find the largest value.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Threshold Computation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The threshold to use for the block is obtained by approximating equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:threshold-pow"

\end_inset

 using a lookup table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Directional Filter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For luma, we use a 7-tap filter along the direction found in the direction
 search.
 For each pixel 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the new value 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

 is computed as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X'=X+[ & f\left(A-X,T\right)+2f\left(B-X,T\right)+\\
 & 3f\left(C-X,T\right)+3f\left(D-X,T\right)+\\
 & 2f\left(E-X,T\right)+f\left(F-X,T\right)]/16
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(d,T\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:threshold-function"

\end_inset

